## The short answer

Name the transition with the team and each former peer. Explain what changed, what did not, how decisions and confidential information will work, and how you will guard against favoritism. Listen to concerns without promising that every relationship will remain identical.

## When this guidance fits

Use this in the first weeks after an internal promotion or interim assignment. Align with your manager on authority, compensation input, performance responsibilities, and decisions that should initially receive support.

> **Stop and get support:** consult HR or your manager on conflicts of interest, close personal or romantic relationships, compensation decisions, active grievances, or policy-specific reporting lines. Do not improvise exceptions in secret.

## 1 — See

Map the role facts: who you evaluate, which information is now confidential, which decisions you own, and where previous friendships could create actual or perceived favoritism. Notice your own temptation either to prove authority or avoid decisions that affect friends.

## 2 — Choose

Hold a clear team reset, then individual conversations. Use transparent work criteria and consistent processes. Seek senior support for the highest-conflict decisions without outsourcing all authority.

## 3 — Say

> “My role has changed, and that changes parts of our relationship. I now own priorities, feedback, and performance decisions for the team. I will use the same visible criteria for everyone and will not discuss another person’s private information. I value the trust we already have, and I want to hear what concerns this transition creates for you.”

Add what has not changed: respect, willingness to listen, and the person’s right to disagree through the team’s normal decision process.

## If they respond with…

### “So we can’t be friends now?”

Avoid a dramatic rule. Explain the boundaries you must keep and acknowledge that the relationship may feel different while both people adjust.

### “I should have gotten the role.”

Do not defend the selection process beyond your knowledge. Listen, acknowledge the disappointment, and offer a separate evidence-based growth conversation.

### “You’re playing favorites.”

Ask for the decision and criterion they are questioning. Review the process and correct it if inconsistent; do not answer a perception concern with “trust me.”

## 4 — Sustain

Publish decision rights and team expectations, establish reliable one-on-ones, and ask your manager to review early high-stakes decisions. Watch patterns in access, stretch work, feedback, and social time. Fairness is demonstrated over repeated choices.

